  "prompt": "What is the remainder when 676767\u2026 unto 900 digit is divided by 999?",
  "response": "Let $N$ be the number consisting of 900 digits where the digits are $676767...67$. We can write $N$ as\n$$ N = 676767...67 = 67 \\times 10^{898} + 67 \\times 10^{896} + ... + 67 \\times 10^2 + 67 \\times 10^0 $$\nThis is a geometric series with first term $a = 67$, common ratio $r = 100$, and number of terms $n = \\frac{900}{2} = 450$. Therefore,\n$$ N = 67 \\sum_{k=0}^{449} (100)^k = 67 \\cdot \\frac{100^{450} - 1}{100-1} = \\frac{67}{99} (100^{450} - 1) $$\nWe want to find the remainder when $N$ is divided by 999. We have $N = \\sum_{k=0}^{299} 676 \\cdot 1000^k + 7$.\n\nAlternatively, we can express $N$ as\n$$ N = \\underbrace{676767...67}_{900 \\text{ digits}} = \\sum_{i=0}^{299} 676 \\times 10^{3i} + 7 \\times 10^{897} $$\nLet us consider the number $M = 676767...67$, where there are 900 digits.\nWe can group the digits in groups of 3 as $676, 767, 676, 767, ..., 67$.\nSince there are 900 digits, we have $\\frac{900}{3} = 300$ groups of 3 digits.\nThen we can write $M$ as\n$$ M = 676 \\times 10^{897} + 767 \\times 10^{894} + 676 \\times 10^{891} + ... + 676 \\times 10^{3} + 767 \\times 10^{0} $$\nWe can write this as\n$$ M = \\sum_{k=0}^{149} 676 \\times 10^{3(299-k)} + \\sum_{k=0}^{149} 767 \\times 10^{3(298-k)} $$\nWe are looking for the remainder when $M$ is divided by 999.\nSince $10^3 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{999}$, we have\n$$ M \\equiv \\sum_{k=0}^{149} 676 \\times 10^{3(299-k)} + \\sum_{k=0}^{149} 767 \\times 10^{3(298-k)} \\equiv \\sum_{k=0}^{149} 676(1)^{299-k} + \\sum_{k=0}^{149} 767(1)^{298-k} \\pmod{999} $$\n$$ M \\equiv 150 \\cdot 676 + 150 \\cdot 767 \\equiv 150 (676 + 767) \\pmod{999} $$\n$$ M \\equiv 150 \\cdot 1443 \\equiv 150 \\cdot (1 \\cdot 999 + 444) \\equiv 150 \\cdot 444 \\equiv 66600 \\pmod{999} $$\nNow $66600 = 66 \\cdot 1000 + 600 \\equiv 66 \\cdot 1 + 600 \\equiv 666 \\pmod{999}$.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{666}$",
